dataCsv.Site_Description: – The wreck is the remains of an 18th Century French and Indian War ship. It lies on a shelf in about 65 to 80 feet of water behind the head of Niagara Shoal. Only the keelson and lower part of the frames remain. The stern of the ship is at 65 feet and has been broken apart. The starboard frames project up about 10 feet from the bottom while the port frames in the stern are almost on the bottom. The keelson is broken at mid-ships and has a slight bend. You can see the hole for the base of the main mast. The bow is in 80 feet of water.
